            },
            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nThis text continues the study of division by four. Therefore, we recommend reading the previous text (<htcite0>) before proceeding.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "320a8e1c-0444-4b6e-b202-e82702db329f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Las cuatro divisiones",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nAs we have seen, to divide means to transform matter into something different without any loss of quantity (<htcite0>). When we divide something once and then divide it again, the conservation of matter still holds true.\n\nDividing again means repeating an action that has already been performed. This is the same idea we observed in the case of multiplication (<htcite2>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "68227419-2430-4359-b902-f6cf87b8941d",
                     "text": "Holmes, F. L.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1985",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b9866acb-fde8-4fcb-b54d-ee7c481cc9e7",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Shared Origin",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Adding the Same Number",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "5",
                        "day": "9"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: The Next Step</b><br /><br />Based on this introductory text, imagine that you have a sheet of paper that has already been divided into two parts — and now you divide each of those parts again by 2.<br /><br />How would you represent this new division?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_exercise",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Exercising\n\nOur goal is to obtain four equal pieces of a sheet of paper.\n\nTo reinforce understanding, we’ll proceed step by step — first by observing visually and then by writing down what we’re doing, just as we did earlier when we divided the sheet into two halves (<htcite0>).\n\n#### The Half\n\nThe first step is to choose one whole sheet.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "112e532d-e8af-40d6-b1b5-527978ee42f3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Two Sides",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"sequenceNum\" class=\"tableTen\"><tr><th colspan=\"2\">Whole sheet</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"height: 300px;\"></td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Representation of a blank sheet.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 2: Fractioning</b><br /><br />1. Fold a sheet in half.<br />2. Now, open it and cut along the fold.</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"sequenceNum\" class=\"tableTen\"><tr><th colspan=\"2\">Divided sheet</th></tr><tr><td style=\"height: 300px;\"></td><td style=\"height: 300px;\"></td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 2</b>: Sheet divided into two pieces.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Finally, we represent this division as a fraction, where the numerator indicates the total we had and the denominator represents the parts obtained.\n\nIf you don’t remember how we reached this result, we recommend reviewing the text where we explained this process (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "112e532d-e8af-40d6-b1b5-527978ee42f3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Two Sides",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac>  <mo>+</mo>  <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 1</b>: Representation of two separate parts.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Dividing Again\n\nIn this stage, we’ll repeat **Practice 1**, but this time we’ll divide each half into two equal pieces:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"sequenceNum\" class=\"tableTen\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\">Divided sheet</th></tr><tr><td style=\"height: 300px;\"></td><td style=\"height: 300px;\"></td><td style=\"height: 300px;\"></td><td style=\"height: 300px;\"></td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 3</b>: Sheet divided into four pieces.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### What Did We Do?\n\nLet’s describe what we want to do.\n\nWe have two pieces, and we want to divide them again into two.\n\nWe can represent this intention as:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 1:</b>: Our goal.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: I’ve Done Something Similar Before</b><br /><br />We already performed an initial division that resulted in <b>Calculation 1</b>.<br /><br />Using <b>Formula 1</b>, how can we represent what we see in <b>Table 3</b>?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "We are repeating the same process: we divided once, and we will divide **again**.\n\nWe previously saw that repeating an addition is the same as multiplying (<htcite0>).\n\nWith that in mind, reflect:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Adding the Same Number",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "5",
                        "day": "9"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: Next Step</b><br /><br />If we’re repeating steps, what would happen if we multiplied <b>Formula 1</b> on both sides of <b>Calculation 1<b/>?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Since we have an equality in **Calculation 1**, to maintain conservation of matter, we can’t change only one side. Therefore, we’ll multiply each number on both sides by **Formula 1**.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mfrac mathsize=\"big\"> <mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>(</mn>  <mn>1</mn> <mn>)</mn><mo>=</mo> <mfrac mathsize=\"big\"> <mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>(</mn> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>)</mn>  <mo>+</mo> <mfrac mathsize=\"big\"> <mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>(</mn>  <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>)</mn> </math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 2</b>: Multiplication representing the process of a new division.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In **Cálculo 2**, we have the multiplication of a number by a fraction on the left side and of fractions on the right side.\n\nWe can standardize this formula by representing the number 1 as a fraction, where the whole is divided by the whole:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mfrac mathsize=\"big\"> <mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>(</mn> <mfrac mathsize=\"big\"> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mrow> </mfrac>  <mn>)</mn><mo>=</mo> <mfrac mathsize=\"big\"> <mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>(</mn> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>)</mn>  <mo>+</mo> <mfrac mathsize=\"big\"> <mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>(</mn>  <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>)</mn> </math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 3</b>: Multiplication representing the new division process, with all numbers written as fractions.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Now that we have only fractions, we can perform fraction multiplication, multiplying numerators together and denominators together (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "db081093-4026-4632-8a78-420ee6d841ad",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Fractions",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mfrac mathsize=\"big\"> <mrow> <mn>2 × 1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2 × 1</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo>  <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2 × 1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2 × 2</mn><mrow> </mfrac>  <mo>+</mo>  <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2 × 1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2 × 2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mfrac mathsize=\"big\"> <mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo>  <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mrow> </mfrac>  <mo>+</mo>  <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 4</b>: Result of fraction multiplication.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Next, we can simplify the left side of Calculation 4, replacing the fraction with the whole (1).\n\nOn the right side, we split the numerators (1 + 1 = 2):",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mrow> </mfrac>  <mo>+</mo>  <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo>  <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mrow> </mfrac>  <mo>+</mo>  <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mrow> </mfrac>  </math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 5</b>: Representation of Table 3.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Through **Calculation 5**, we can represent exactly what we see in **Table 3**: four equal pieces make up one whole sheet.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "O numerador de uma fração representa o todo?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "A parte superior da fração representa a totalidade que está sendo compartilhada entre as quantidades no denominador, a parte inferior."
      },
      {
         "question": "Na multiplicação da fração, multiplicamos o todo (numerador) pelo todo e as partes (denominador) pelas partes?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "Quando realizamos multiplicação entre frações, sempre multiplicamos quantidades iguais."
      }
   ],
